{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"65f1e362-228d-441d-b36b-a559bd9f878e","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here automatically.\n\n2. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps:\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS.\n\n3. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same `.ips` files.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and register state — usually enough to start debugging without `createdump`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"06eb7b0a-d683-4148-b2a4-4346727e96c3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"784E:113DA4:46DF53:524EFD:69FA9DAF"},"id":"b69b224e-7c4d-4758-a297-7c3eefb8ea7e","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:47:36.022Z","parentId":"9c919d64-ca94-4b92-82c0-42d74846a5eb"}
